               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350511-name-1265" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1265" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1265" type="surname" value="HOGG"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1265" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM HOGG</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Queen-street, Horsleydown. I was at Greenwich fair on Easter Monday, between two and three o'clock—I did not feel my handkerchief taken—the constable tapped me on the shoulder and showed me my handkerchief—I am sure it is mine—I had been in the fair about three quarters of an hour.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350511-name-1266" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1266" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1266" type="surname" value="DYKE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1266" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM DYKE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a policeman. I was in the fair about a quar<lb></lb>ter-past two o'clock, and saw the prisoner following the prosecutor, who had a friend with him—the prisoner was alone—I saw him poll the hand<lb></lb>kerchief about three inches from the prosecutor's pocket at first, and when he got about twelve or fourteen yards further, I saw him take it out entirely—I caught hold of him directly, and he dropped it on the ground—I detained him—there wat not much crowd then—he denied the charge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
